<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1539,2032]" pageId="3" pageNumber="177">
<emphasis box="[199,420,1539,1564]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="177">Macropterous male</emphasis>
. Similar to female in structure and coloration, though smaller and with fore tibiae and tibiae paler (
<figureCitation box="[297,366,1575,1600]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1946,1969]" captionTargetBox="[196,1385,533,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[196,1385,507,1920]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Holopothrips striatus. (1) Male. (2) Larva. (3) Ventral view of head and prosternum. (4) Dorsal view of head. (5) Antenna." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/177974/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="177">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); abdominal sternites VII and VIII each with one transverse pore plate extending across the posterior region (interrupted medially on VII) and two oval pore plates placed anterolaterally (
<figureCitation box="[1216,1285,1611,1636]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 9" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1446,1469]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1426]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1426]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 9. Holopothrips striatus. (6) Pronotum (left side). (7) Pelta. (8) Dorsal view of pterothorax and first abdominal segment. (9) Male abdominal sternites VII – VIII." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/177975/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="177">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); S2 setae on abdominal tergite IX acute and not shortened.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1539,2032]" pageId="3" pageNumber="177">
Measurements of male (
<typeStatus box="[471,575,1684,1708]" pageId="3" pageNumber="177">paratype</typeStatus>
): Length about 2,625; head length 293, greatest width across cheeks 210, po length 77; tergite IX setae S1 225, S2 247; length (width) of antennal segments 
<date box="[1082,1202,1719,1744]" pageId="3" pageNumber="177" value="1960-02" valueMax="1960-08-31" valueMin="1960-02-00">II–VIII 60</date>
(30), 97(30), 80(32), 75(30), 70(22), 62(22), 32(12), respectively.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1539,2032]" pageId="3" pageNumber="177">
<emphasis box="[199,292,1792,1815]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="177">Larva II</emphasis>
. Body color largely white but antenna and abdominal segments IX–X brown, transverse bands of red internal pigmentation present in thorax and abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[759,828,1827,1852]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1946,1969]" captionTargetBox="[196,1385,533,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[196,1385,507,1920]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Holopothrips striatus. (1) Male. (2) Larva. (3) Ventral view of head and prosternum. (4) Dorsal view of head. (5) Antenna." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/177974/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="177">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
